---
export const prerender = true;
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
---

<BlogLayout
  title="Best Words with Double Letters in Scrabble — Turn Duplicates Into Points"
  description="Holding duplicate tiles? These double-letter words turn EE, OO, LL, SS, TT and other repeats into high-scoring plays instead of dead weight on your rack."
  keywords="double letter words scrabble, duplicate tiles strategy, ee words scrabble, oo words scrabble, double letters high scoring, scrabble duplicate tiles, words with repeated letters"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Best Words with Double Letters in Scrabble — Turn Duplicates Into Points",
    "description": "Holding duplicate tiles? These double-letter words turn EE, OO, LL, SS, TT and other repeats into high-scoring plays instead of dead weight on your rack.",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-15",
    "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com" },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/best-words-with-double-letters" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Are double letters bad in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Double letters are not inherently bad. While duplicates reduce flexibility, many high-scoring words require them — COFFEE (11 pts), PIZZAZZ (45 pts), BALLOON (9 pts). The key is knowing which words use your duplicates so you can play them quickly rather than holding two identical tiles for multiple turns." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What are the best Scrabble words with double letters?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Top double-letter words include PIZZAZZ (45 pts, double Z), FRIZZES (28 pts, double Z), JAZZIER (32 pts, double Z), DAZZLE (25 pts, double Z), TOFFEE (12 pts, double F+E), COFFEE (14 pts, double F+E), and BALLOON (9 pts, double L). Words with double Z score highest because Z is worth 10 points." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Should I exchange duplicate tiles in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Only exchange if you cannot form any word using the duplicate AND your best play scores under 12-15 points. Common doubles like EE, SS, LL, and TT appear in hundreds of valid words, so you can almost always play them. Rare doubles like VV or QQ (which has no valid words) should be exchanged immediately — one tile at minimum." }
      }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <a href="/blog/strategy/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors text-gray-300">Strategy</a>
      </nav>

      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Best Words with Double Letters in Scrabble — Turn Duplicates Into Points</h1>

      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-15">June 15, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>6 min read</span>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔤</span> Word Finder</a>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">
        You draw your tiles and see two E's staring back. Or two L's. Or two S's. That sinking feeling of "dead weight" hits — but it shouldn't. Duplicate tiles aren't a curse. They're an invitation to play some of Scrabble's most satisfying words. The trick is knowing which words consume your doubles quickly and score well doing it.
      </p>

      <!-- Hero card -->
      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">👑 Key Truth</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">DOUBLES ≠ DEAD WEIGHT</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">1,400+ valid words contain double letters in tournament dictionaries</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">EE appears in over 1,000 words. OO in 400+. LL in 800+. Your duplicates aren't limiting your options — you just need to know where to aim them.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why Duplicates Feel Problematic (But Aren't)</h2>

      <p>The instinct to panic when you see duplicates comes from a real place: two identical tiles reduce your letter variety from 7 unique tiles to 6. That's one fewer combination available for word formation. But this math only tells half the story.</p>

      <!-- Stat strip -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">1,000+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Words with EE</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">800+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Words with LL</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">400+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Words with OO</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">600+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Words with SS</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>The English language loves double letters. Think of everyday words: COFFEE, STREET, BALLOON, PIZZAZZ. These aren't obscure tournament words — they're common vocabulary that scores well. The real problem isn't having duplicates. It's <span class="text-white font-medium">not knowing which words use them</span>.</p>

      <!-- Insight callout -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 The Duplicate Advantage</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Players who know their double-letter words actually <span class="text-white font-medium">welcome</span> duplicates. Two S's means potential ASSESS, POSSESS, STRESS. Two E's means ESTEEM, GEESE, TEEPEE. The tiles become an asset, not a liability.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Best Words by Double-Letter Pair</h2>

      <p>Here are the highest-scoring words for each common duplicate tile pair you'll encounter. Memorise the top 2-3 for each group and you'll never be stuck with duplicates again.</p>

      <!-- Table -->
      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Double</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Best Words</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Score</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400 font-bold">ZZ</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">PIZZAZZ, FRIZZES, JAZZIER</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">45, 28, 32</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400 font-bold">EE</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">SQUEEZE, TEEPEE, ESTEEM</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">24, 8, 8</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400 font-bold">OO</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">VOODOO, HOODOO, FOOTWORK</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">10, 10, 18</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400 font-bold">LL</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">SKILLFUL, THRILLER, ENROLLED</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">15, 11, 9</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400 font-bold">SS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">ASSASSIN, POSSESS, SCISSORS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">8, 11, 12</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400 font-bold">TT</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">ATTIC, KITTEN, BUTTER</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">7, 10, 8</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400 font-bold">NN</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">CINNAMON, INNOCENT, ANNOUNCE</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">12, 11, 11</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400 font-bold">RR</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">IRREGULAR, SURROUND, MIRRORS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">10, 10, 9</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400 font-bold">DD</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">SHREDDED, PADDOCK, WADDING</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">13, 17, 12</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-amber-400 font-bold">FF</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-300">SCAFFOLD, DAFFODIL, STUFFING</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">16, 15, 12</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- Pill badges for most common doubles -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-3">
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">EE</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">most common</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">OO</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">frequent</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">LL</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">versatile</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">SS</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">hook-friendly</span>
        </span>
        <span class="inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 text-sm">
          <span class="text-white font-bold">TT</span><span class="text-blue-400 text-xs">common</span>
        </span>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Doubles on Premium Squares — Multiplied Value</h2>

      <p>Double-letter words become especially powerful when the repeated letter lands on a premium square. Because you're playing the same high-value letter twice, one of them has a strong chance of landing on a DLS or TLS.</p>

      <!-- Card grid showing premium combos -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ ZZ on DLS</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">PIZZA with Z on DLS = Z counts as 20 pts. Total word score jumps from 25 to 35 base.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ FF on TLS</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">SCAFFOLD with F on TLS = F counts as 12 pts. Premium placement adds 8 bonus points.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ DD + DWS</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">PADDOCK across DWS = entire 17-pt word doubled to 34. Doubles help reach premium rows.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ LL in 7-letter bingo</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">THRILLER as a bingo = 11 pts + 50 bonus = 61 pts. LL words are strong bingo candidates.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>The strategic lesson: when you draw doubles of a high-point tile (FF, ZZ, DD), don't panic — aim for premium squares. You only need one of the two to land on a bonus square to dramatically inflate your score.</p>

      <!-- Comparison cards -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Play Double on Premium</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">DAZZLE with Z on TLS scores 40+ points. Premium placement transforms a good word into a great turn.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10">
          <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✗ Dump to Draw Fresh</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Exchanging both Z's sacrifices a turn. Only do this if the board has zero premium square access for ZZ words.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">When to Hold vs Dump Duplicates</h2>

      <p>Not all doubles deserve the same treatment. Your decision depends on three factors: tile value, available board positions, and how many valid words use that specific double.</p>

      <!-- Purple strategy tiles -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Always hold EE:</span> Over 1,000 valid words contain EE. You'll play them within 1-2 turns. ESTEEM, GEESE, CREEP, SLEEVE, BREEZE — options everywhere.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Always hold SS:</span> Double S is a gift. ASSESS, STRESS, POSSESS, BLESS + any S-hook. Two S's means you can pluralize AND keep one for later.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Hold LL if board has space:</span> BALLOON, THRILLER, PARALLEL — excellent bingo candidates. Only dump one L if the board is completely closed.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Dump one V if you have VV:</span> Very few words use double V. Play one immediately in a short word (VIVA, VALVE, VIVID) even at low score to free your rack.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Exchange UU immediately:</span> Almost no valid words contain double U. Don't waste turns hoping — exchange at least one U and invest in a better draw.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Inline cross-links -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">📚 Dig Deeper</p>
        <div class="grid gap-2">
          <a href="/blog/rack-management-basics/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">Rack Management Basics — when to exchange, what to keep, and vowel-consonant balance</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/creating-parallel-plays/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">Creating Parallel Plays — doubles are ideal for adjacent word formations</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Using Doubles for Parallel Plays</h2>

      <p>Here's where duplicates become genuinely advantageous. Parallel plays — placing your word alongside an existing word — often require the same letter to appear in multiple positions. If the board has a word ending in -EED and you need to place letters below it, having two E's gives you more valid arrangements.</p>

      <!-- Insight callout -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-cyan-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🎯 Parallel Play Advantage</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Double-letter tiles let you mirror patterns on the board. If an existing word has <span class="text-white font-medium">repeated letters in adjacent cells</span>, your matching duplicates create valid 2-letter cross-words in both positions simultaneously.</p>
      </div>

      <p>Common parallels enabled by doubles: LL below LL (AL/AL), EE beside EE (forming valid EE cross-words), SS beside words ending in S. These patterns score multiple cross-words from tiles that would otherwise feel redundant. The next time you draw duplicate tiles, scan the board for parallel opportunities before considering an exchange.</p>

      <!-- Related Articles -->
      <aside class="border-t border-gray-800 mt-12 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Related Articles</h3>
        <div class="grid gap-3">
          <a href="/blog/words-with-double-letters/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Words with Double Letters — Complete Reference List</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/best-words-for-premium-squares/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Best Words for Premium Squares — Maximize DLS, TLS, DWS, TWS</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/rack-leave-explained/" class="flex items-center gap-3 p-3 rounded-lg border border-gray-800 hover:border-blue-700 hover:bg-blue-900/10 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-blue-500 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">Rack Leave Explained — Why What You Keep Matters More Than What You Play</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </aside>

      <!-- CTA -->
      <div class="not-prose mt-10 p-5 bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-900/20 to-blue-800/20 border border-blue-800 rounded-xl">
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4 flex-wrap">
          <p class="text-sm text-blue-300 font-medium">🔤 Find your highest-scoring double-letter words — free, instant, no signup needed</p>
          <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-blue-500 hover:bg-blue-400 text-gray-950 text-sm font-semibold transition-colors">Open Word Finder →</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose mt-8 text-center">
        <a href="/blog/" class="text-sm text-gray-400 hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Back to all articles</a>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</BlogLayout>
